                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d485">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1"
                        >Baker, Charles</persName>/21: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hankow (<persName
                            corresp="frus1932v03#p_AWA1" type="from">Adams</persName>) to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-09T12:00:00+08:00"
                            >February 9, 1932—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received February 9—6:55
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>26. My No. 22, February 2, 6 p.m. A further written appeal from <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName> has been received. He states
                    that he is suffering from intense cold and lack of proper furnishings and that
                    he is becoming very weak. His captors have reduced the price of his release to
                    $50,000. The Ichang agent of the Yangtze Rapid Steamship Company is now on board
                    the <hi rend="italic">Panay</hi> at Mopanshih negotiating with the Communists
                    for <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s release.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_AWA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Adams</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
